        "intro_content": "<p>The <strong>santoku knife</strong> is Japan's most popular <strong>kitchen knife</strong>, named for its three virtues: slicing, dicing, and mincing. Lighter and more agile than a Western chef knife, the santoku delivers precision cuts through vegetables, proteins, and herbs without the heft. XinZuo santoku knives feature 67-layer Damascus steel with a hard 10Cr15CoMoV core, forged in Yangjiang using techniques refined over generations. If you want one knife that handles almost everything in an Australian kitchen, the santoku knife is a compelling choice. For dedicated vegetable work, pair it with a nakiri. For heavier tasks, consider a gyuto or chef knife.</p>",
